Question 2: Write your code in the code chunk and your text answer after the code chunk.

y <- c(105,69,86,100,82,111,104,110,87,108,87,90,94,113,112,98,80,97,95,111,114,89,95,126,98)

xbar <- mean(y)

n <- length(y)

s <- sd(y)

# 90% conf. int., so we set alpha to 0.1
alpha <- 0.1

criticalt <- qt(alpha/2, n-1, lower.tail = F)

lower <- xbar - criticalt * s / sqrt(n)
upper <- xbar + criticalt * s / sqrt(n)

The 90% confidence interval for the average student IQ in the school is [93.9599275, 102.9200725]

Question 3: Write your code in the code chunk and your text answer after the code chunk.

# H0: average IQ in the school is higher than 100
# Ha: average IQ in the school is not higher than 100

results <- t.test(y, alternative = "greater", mu = 100, conf.level = 0.95)

The p-value is 0.7215383, which is more than 0.05. We therefore fail to reject the null hypothesis, which means that the population mean for the IQ of students at the school could be less than 100.

Question 5: Write your code in the code chunk and your text answer after the code chunk.

boxplot(expenditure$Y ~ expenditure$Region)

results <- t.test(expenditure$Y[expenditure$Region == "West"], alternative = "two.sided", mu = 100, conf.level = 0.95)

A side-by-side boxplot is most appropriate to visualize the relationship between Y and Region. On average, the West has the highest per capita expenditure on public education. The confidence interval for the true average per capita expenditure in the West is [95.2805225, 116.7194775].
